      {
        "paragraph_index": 1,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insight\n\nThe very low (negative) pKa₁ means the first proton of oxalic acid is almost completely dissociated in aqueous solution — it behaves as a strong acid for its first dissociation. The second dissociation (pKa₂ ≈ 3.8) is typical of a moderately weak carboxylic acid. The large gap of ~5 pKa units between the two steps reflects the electrostatic difficulty of removing a second proton from an already negatively charged species, compounded by the close proximity of the two carboxylate groups on this small dicarboxylic acid.",
